022: \u0022Deactivate all unused accounts\u0022,\n        \u0022Selected\u0022: false,\n        \u0022RecordCreated\u0022: \u00222025-07-28T10:29:06.64\u002B02:00\u0022,\n        \u0022RecordUpdatedBy\u0022: \u002221c7c5cd-b373-43a6-aa40-aed4533686c2\u0022,\n        \u0022Id\u0022: \u002250c49bfd-8e05-42b1-adb4-b7cc4ff9f9da\u0022,\n        \u0022RecordCreatedBy\u0022: \u002221c7c5cd-b373-43a6-aa40-aed4533686c2\u0022,\n        \u0022RecordUpdated\u0022: \u00222025-11-06T10:10:58.197\u002B01:00\u0022\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n  \n   Get the details of a specific item from the list \n To target a specific record, you better create a new API Data Page this time with  {id}  in the name. You can also use the existing API created in the previous step, define a filter based on the Id, and ignore it if the Id is empty \u2014 that is, display all existing Ids. However, having a separate API is usually clearer. \n   Parameter mapping \n To select a specific record by its Id, you need to use a parameter. You define this parameter via Parameter Mappings on the relevant API data page: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/054e94792a151767ed94e95b09ccaa5bc0ca7b6e.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a parameter mapping section labeled \u0022Parameter Mapping: Task_parId.\u0022 The visible UI text includes fields under (Info) such as \u0022Schema Item\u0022 with attributes like \u0022Ancestors\u0022 (False), \u0022Inheritable\u0022 (False), and \u0022Name\u0022 (Task_parId). Beneath the (Lists) section, it shows \u0022IsList\u0022 (False) and \u0022ListSeparator.\u0022 In the (Mapping) section, fields include \u0022DatastructureEntityName,\u0022 \u0022DefaultValue,\u0022 and \u0022MappedParameter\u0022 (id). The interface appears to be part of a data modeling tool or software for configuring parameters associated with a task.\n\n\n  \n   Filtering \n Next you need to configure the Data Structure Filter Set \u2013   Method   \u2013 that retrieves the record\u2019s data based on its Id. Your Data Page configuration may look like this: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/59242013445428e7aa2804e0fe78bb69aa65c3fa.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a user interface for a data page configuration labeled \u0022Data Page: api/public/task/{id}\u0022. It contains several sections including \u0022Info,\u0022 \u0022Caching,\u0022 \u0022InputValidation,\u0022 \u0022JSON,\u0022 \u0022Logging,\u0022 \u0022Misc,\u0022 \u0022Page,\u0022 and \u0022Security.\u0022 Visible text includes \u0022Name: api/public/task/{id}\u0022, \u0022CacheMaxAge\u0022, \u0022OmitJsonMainElement: False\u0022, \u0022OmitJsonRootElement: False\u0022, \u0022DataStructure: Task_API\u0022, \u0022Method: Get Id\u0022, and \u0022MimeType: application/json\u0022. The apparent purpose of this configuration interface is to define settings and parameters for accessing a public API endpoint related to tasks.\n\n\n  \n The URL might look like this: \n  https://localhost/api/public/task/5784a17e-15fe-4f1e-b612-6a35055f4c0c  \n This request will return the details (based on your Data Structure) of that record: \n  {\n  \u0022ROOT\u0022: {\n    \u0022Task\u0022: [\n      {\n        \u0022Status_Id\u0022: \u0022376ae614-1381-4ff5-b894-9c96c7978ead\u0022,\n        \u0022Name\u0022: \u0022Create accounts\u0022,\n        \u0022AssignedTo_Id\u0022: \u002221c7c5cd-b373-43a6-aa40-aed4533686c2\u0022,\n        \u0022DueDate\u0022: \u00222025-11-30T00:00:00\u002B01:00\u0022,\n        \u0022Priority_Id\u0022: \u0022bae03329-491c-4b09-8345-f8d26f027e9b\u0022,\n        \u0022NotificationSent\u0022: false,\n        \u0022Description\u0022: \u0022Create user accounts for all new users who joined this month\u0022,\n        \u0022Selected\u0022: false,\n        \u0022RecordCreated\u0022: \u00222025-02-18T13:56:18.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"20